{"questionId":"17414","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Peter, the Principal of a college, believes that there is an association between the score in a&nbsp;Mathematics test, <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"X\">\n  <mi>X</mi>\n</math></span>, and the time taken to run 500 m, <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"Y\">\n  <mi>Y</mi>\n</math></span> seconds, of his students.&nbsp;The following paired data are collected.</p>\n<p><img src=\"__IMG__/e6e6a4b1ad2ecc54d9835bbdae02406fc919e51c.png\"></p>\n<p>It can be assumed that <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\left( {X{\\text{, }}Y} \\right)\">\n  <mrow>\n    <mo>(</mo>\n    <mrow>\n      <mi>X</mi>\n      <mrow>\n        <mtext>,&nbsp;</mtext>\n      </mrow>\n      <mi>Y</mi>\n    </mrow>\n    <mo>)</mo>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span> follow a bivariate normal distribution with product moment&nbsp;correlation coefficient <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\rho \">\n  <mi>ρ</mi>\n</math></span>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>State suitable hypotheses <span class=\"mjpage\"><math alttext=\"{H_0}\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <msub> <mi>H</mi> <mn>0</mn> </msub> </mrow> </math></span> and <span class=\"mjpage\"><math alttext=\"{H_1}\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <msub> <mi>H</mi> <mn>1</mn> </msub> </mrow> </math></span> to test Peter’s claim, using a two-tailed test.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math alttext=\"{H_0}\\,{\\text{:}}\\,\\rho&nbsp; = 0\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <msub> <mi>H</mi> <mn>0</mn> </msub> </mrow> <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace> <mrow> <mtext>:</mtext> </mrow> <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace> <mi>ρ</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mn>0</mn> </math></span>&nbsp; &nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math alttext=\"{H_1}\\,{\\text{:}}\\,\\rho&nbsp; \\ne 0\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <msub> <mi>H</mi> <mn>1</mn> </msub> </mrow> <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace> <mrow> <mtext>:</mtext> </mrow> <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace> <mi>ρ</mi> <mo>≠</mo> <mn>0</mn> </math></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> It must be <span class=\"mjpage\"><math alttext=\"\\rho \" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mi>ρ</mi> </math></span>.</p>\n<p><em><strong>[1 mark]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"17414","referenceCode":"19N.3.AHL.TZ0.Hsp_1a.i","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"State suitable hypotheses H 0 and H 1 to test Peter’s claim, using a two-tailed test.","paper":"3","level":"HL","questionNumber":"a.i","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4.4—Pearsons, scatter diagrams, eqn of y on x","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","AHL 4.18—T and Z test, type I and II errors"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}